The first engine kills the most common $O(n^2)$ shape in existence: *for each element, scan everything else looking for a partner*.

Instead, walk the array **once**. At each element, ask the map a question about elements you've *already passed*, then record the current element and move on. The inner scan becomes a single $O(1)$ lookup.

> [!ANALOGY]
> It's a coat check. Instead of running back through the whole party asking everyone "are you my partner?", every guest who has already arrived left a ticket at the desk. You walk in, ask the desk one question — *"is ticket `target − mine` here?"* — and either get an instant match or leave your own ticket and step aside.

The canonical form is Two Sum:

```cpp
// Canonical: Two Sum — return indices of the two numbers adding to target.
vector<int> twoSum(vector<int>& nums, int target) {
    unordered_map<int, int> seen;              // value -> index it lives at
    for (int i = 0; i < (int)nums.size(); ++i) {
        int need = target - nums[i];           // the partner I'm looking for
        auto it = seen.find(need);
        if (it != seen.end())                  // partner already passed by?
            return {it->second, i};
        seen[nums[i]] = i;                      // record AFTER checking (avoid self-pair)
    }
    return {};                                  // problem usually guarantees a solution
}
```

[[fig:m01-two-sum-lookup]]

Notice the shape: **query first, insert second**. When you're standing at index `i`, the map contains exactly the elements at indices `0..i-1` — so any match you find is automatically an *earlier* element, and an element can never match itself.

> [!PITFALL] The #1 bug in this whole module
> Inserting the current element *before* querying lets it pair with itself: with `nums = [3, 5]` and `target = 6`, insert-first happily returns `{0, 0}`. Burn the ordering rule into your fingers: **query for the partner, then insert yourself.**

Second engine: when the question is about **counts** — duplicates, anagrams, majority elements, "top K frequent" — count first, reason about the counts second.

Two containers do this job:

- `unordered_map<Key, int>` — for arbitrary keys (integers with huge range, strings, pairs you encode).
- A **fixed array** like `int cnt[26]` or `array<int,26>` — when the domain is small and known (lowercase letters, digits 0–9). This version is *much* faster: no hashing, no allocation, and `==` compares two signatures in one shot.

```cpp
// Anagram signature via a 26-slot frequency array.
array<int,26> freq(const string& s) {
    array<int,26> c{};                          // zero-initialized
    for (char ch : s) c[ch - 'a']++;
    return c;
}
bool isAnagram(const string& a, const string& b) {
    return a.size() == b.size() && freq(a) == freq(b);
}
```

The same signature idea powers **Group Anagrams**: two strings are anagrams iff they have the same canonical key (their sorted form, or their count signature) — so use that key in a map and the groups build themselves.

> [!EXAMPLE]
> `isAnagram("listen", "silent")`: both build the signature `{e:1, i:1, l:1, n:1, s:1, t:1}` spread over 26 slots → arrays compare equal → `true`. `isAnagram("rat", "car")`: slot `r` and `a` match but `t` vs `c` differ → `false`. One pass each, $O(n)$ total.

> [!EXAM] Under time pressure
> If the domain is `a`–`z` or similarly tiny, reach for `array<int,26>` without thinking. It's faster to type, faster to run, and immune to hash-collision worst cases that occasionally bite `unordered_map` on adversarial Codility tests.

Third engine, and the one that decides medium-difficulty OA problems: **prefix sums**.

Define `pre[i] = nums[0] + ... + nums[i-1]`, with `pre[0] = 0` (the empty prefix). Then any subarray sum falls out by subtraction:

$$\text{sum}(l..r) = pre[r+1] - pre[l]$$

[[fig:m01-prefix-sum]]

That identity turns *"count subarrays with sum $k$"* into a complement-lookup problem — literally Two Sum in one higher dimension. A subarray ending at `r` with sum `k` exists for every earlier prefix equal to `pre[r+1] − k`. So: keep a running prefix and a map from *prefix value → how many times it has occurred*, and at each step count the matching earlier prefixes.

```cpp
// Count subarrays summing to k. O(n) time, O(n) space.
int subarraySum(vector<int>& nums, int k) {
    unordered_map<long long, int> cnt;          // prefix value -> how many times seen
    cnt[0] = 1;                                  // empty prefix: needed for subarrays starting at index 0
    long long pre = 0;
    int ans = 0;
    for (int x : nums) {
        pre += x;
        // a previous prefix p with (pre - p == k) closes a valid subarray
        auto it = cnt.find(pre - k);
        if (it != cnt.end()) ans += it->second;
        cnt[pre]++;                              // record current prefix AFTER counting
    }
    return ans;
}
```

The same query-then-insert ordering rule from Engine 1 applies here, and there are two extra details that separate accepted from wrong-answer:

> [!PITFALL] The two lines everyone gets wrong
> **1. `cnt[0] = 1`.** Without the seed, any subarray that starts at index 0 — i.e. a full prefix that itself equals `k` — is never counted. **2. `long long` for the running sum.** Prefix sums overflow `int` fast; make it a habit before the OA punishes you for it.

> [!WARNING] Sliding window is a trap here
> If values can be **negative**, the grow/shrink sliding window silently gives wrong answers — shrinking the window no longer monotonically decreases the sum. "Count subarrays with sum k, negatives allowed" is a prefix-map problem, full stop.

deepdives.answer:
**Why naive fails.** The obvious move is `total_product / nums[i]` — but division is banned, and it explodes anyway the moment a zero appears in the array. Recomputing each product with its own loop is $O(n^2)$.

> [!INTUITION]
> `out[i]` splits perfectly at position `i`: it is *(product of everything strictly left of `i`)* × *(product of everything strictly right of `i`)*. Each half is a running product you can accumulate in a single directional sweep — one pass left-to-right, one pass right-to-left.

[[fig:m01-left-right]]

**The algorithm, step by step:**

1. **Left pass:** write into `out[i]` the product of all elements strictly left of `i`. Start an accumulator `pre = 1`; at each `i`, store `pre` *first*, then multiply `nums[i]` in. (So `out[0] = 1` — nothing is left of index 0.)
2. **Right pass:** sweep backwards with a second accumulator `suf = 1`, multiplying `out[i] *= suf` before folding `nums[i]` into `suf`.

```cpp
vector<int> productExceptSelf(vector<int>& nums) {
    int n = nums.size();
    vector<int> out(n, 1);
    int pre = 1;
    for (int i = 0; i < n; ++i) { out[i] = pre; pre *= nums[i]; } // left products
    int suf = 1;
    for (int i = n - 1; i >= 0; --i) { out[i] *= suf; suf *= nums[i]; } // × right products
    return out;
}
```

**Complexity:** $O(n)$ time, $O(1)$ extra space — the output array doesn't count against you. Zeros handle themselves with no special-casing: a zero at position `j` simply makes every left-product past `j` and every right-product before `j` zero, which is exactly correct.

**What generalizes:** the *store-before-fold* two-pass shape — "answer at `i` = f(everything left) ⊕ f(everything right)" — reappears constantly: prefix/suffix maxima in trapping-rain-water-style problems, prefix XORs, and DP problems that split around an index. When you see "except self" or "on both sides of i", think two sweeps.

**Why naive fails.** Enumerating all $O(n^2)$ subarrays is too slow. And here's the trap that catches most people: because values can be **negative**, the grow/shrink sliding window is *wrong*, not just slow — shrinking the window no longer monotonically decreases the sum, so the window logic silently produces wrong answers.

> [!KEY]
> `sum(l..r) = pre[r+1] − pre[l]`. So a subarray **ending** at `r` with sum `k` exists for every earlier prefix with `pre[l] = pre[r+1] − k`. That is a complement lookup — *exactly Two Sum*, except you count how many earlier prefixes match instead of returning one index.

[[fig:m01-prefix-sum]]

**The algorithm:** maintain a running prefix sum `pre` and a map `cnt : prefix value → occurrences so far`. At each element: add `cnt[pre − k]` to the answer (every matching earlier prefix closes one valid subarray ending here), *then* record the current `pre`. Seed `cnt[0] = 1` so a subarray starting at index 0 — one whose entire prefix equals `k` — gets counted.

```cpp
int subarraySum(vector<int>& nums, int k) {
    unordered_map<long long, int> cnt;
    cnt[0] = 1;                 // the empty prefix
    long long pre = 0;
    int ans = 0;
    for (int x : nums) {
        pre += x;
        auto it = cnt.find(pre - k);   // every earlier prefix equal to (pre-k)
        if (it != cnt.end()) ans += it->second; // ...closes a valid subarray
        cnt[pre]++;                    // record AFTER counting
    }
    return ans;
}
```

**Complexity:** $O(n)$ time, $O(n)$ space. The two spots people get wrong: the seed `cnt[0] = 1`, and the query-before-insert order.

**What generalizes:** "count subarrays where *(cumulative quantity)* hits a target" almost always reduces to *prefix + complement map* — subarray sums divisible by `k` (store `pre mod k`), equal 0s and 1s (map 0→−1, look for equal prefixes), XOR targets (prefix XOR). Learn the reduction once, reuse it for years.

**Why naive fails.** Sorting gives an easy answer but costs $O(n \log n)$ — explicitly not the target. Expanding outward from every element while re-scanning the array is $O(n^2)$.

> [!INTUITION]
> Dump everything into a hash set. Now here's the whole trick: a number `x` can only be the **start** of a run if `x − 1` is *not* in the set. Walk upward (`x, x+1, x+2, …`) **only from starts**. Every run is then walked exactly once, from its unique starting point — so the total inner-loop work across the entire outer loop is at most $n$ steps.

[[fig:m01-run-start]]

```cpp
int longestConsecutive(vector<int>& nums) {
    unordered_set<int> s(nums.begin(), nums.end());
    int best = 0;
    for (int x : s) {
        if (s.count(x - 1)) continue;           // not a sequence start — skip
        int len = 1, cur = x;
        while (s.count(cur + 1)) { ++cur; ++len; }  // walk the run once
        best = max(best, len);
    }
    return best;
}
```

**Trace** on `[100,4,200,1,3,2]`: the set is `{1,2,3,4,100,200}`. `4` has `3` in the set → skip. `1` has no `0` → walk `1→2→3→4`, length 4. `100` has no `99` → run of 1. `200` likewise. Answer **4**.

**Complexity:** $O(n)$ time, $O(n)$ space. The guard `if (s.count(x - 1)) continue;` **is** the algorithm — delete it and every element of a length-$m$ run launches its own walk, collapsing you back to $O(n^2)$.

> [!PITFALL]
> Iterate over the *set*, not the original array — duplicated values in `nums` would otherwise repeat identical walks. And when asked "but there's a while inside a for — isn't that $O(n^2)$?", the answer is amortization: each set element is stepped onto by *some* walk at most once in total.

**What generalizes:** the *"only start work from canonical starting points"* idea — you'll meet it again when you only launch DFS floods from unvisited cells, and in interval problems where only left endpoints begin a merge.

**Why naive fails.** A hash set answers it in $O(n)$ time but $O(n)$ space — the hard version forbids that. Sorting costs $O(n \log n)$.

> [!KEY]
> For an array of length `n`, the answer **must** lie in `[1, n+1]` (if all of `1..n` are present, it's `n+1`; otherwise one of them is missing). Everything outside `[1, n]` is noise. So use the array *itself* as the hash table: value `v`'s "home" is index `v − 1`. Put everyone home, then the first index `i` where `nums[i] != i + 1` reveals the answer `i + 1`.

**The trick — cyclic swapping.** At each position `i`, *while* the current value `v = nums[i]` is in range `[1, n]` and not already sitting in its home slot (`nums[v-1] != v`), swap it home. It must be a `while`, not an `if`: the swap drops a brand-new value into position `i`, and that value may itself need to travel. The guard `nums[v-1] != v` is what stops duplicates from swapping back and forth forever.

[[fig:m01-home-swap]]

```cpp
int firstMissingPositive(vector<int>& nums) {
    int n = nums.size();
    for (int i = 0; i < n; ++i) {
        while (nums[i] > 0 && nums[i] <= n && nums[nums[i]-1] != nums[i])
            swap(nums[i], nums[nums[i]-1]);      // send nums[i] to its home index
    }
    for (int i = 0; i < n; ++i)
        if (nums[i] != i + 1) return i + 1;      // first slot not holding its home value
    return n + 1;                                // 1..n all present
}
```

**Trace** on `[3,4,-1,1]`: `i=0`: 3 → home index 2, swap → `[-1,4,3,1]`; −1 is out of range, stop. `i=1`: 4 → index 3 → `[-1,1,3,4]`; now 1 → index 0 → `[1,-1,3,4]`; −1 stops. `i=2,3`: already home. Scan: index 1 holds −1 ≠ 2 → answer **2**.

**Complexity:** $O(n)$ time — every swap parks at least one element permanently in its home, so total swaps ≤ n — and $O(1)$ extra space.

> [!PITFALL]
> Writing the duplicate guard as `nums[i] != i + 1` instead of `nums[nums[i]-1] != nums[i]` reintroduces the infinite loop on inputs like `[1,1]`: the two equal values would swap with each other forever. Compare the value against *its home slot's occupant*, not against the current position.

**What generalizes:** whenever values are bounded by the array length (`[1, n]` or `[0, n−1]`) and space is forbidden, think *index-as-hash*: swap-to-home (this problem), or sign-marking (Find All Numbers Disappeared).
